{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415045"},"attributes":{"position":44,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:01:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:01:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2511"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506050"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:39:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:39:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2511"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"2511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2511"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.13,0.21,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53314"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2511"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38763"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"593"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2332"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7530"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12169"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48134"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53314"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of heavy vaginal bleeding and cramping lower abdominal pain. She is nine weeks pregnant with her first child. She reports having soaked a pad each hour and passing large clots. Her pain has been increasing in intensity. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Pelvic examination reveals blood on the external genitalia. On speculum examination, the cervical os is visibly dilated with products of conception visible at the os, and there is ongoing light bleeding. Transvaginal ultrasound shows an intrauterine gestational sac with a crown-rump length of 17 mm and fetal cardiac activity present at 60 beats per minute.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inevitable miscarriage","Threatened miscarriage","Incomplete miscarriage","Ectopic pregnancy","Missed miscarriage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with a miscarriage in progress. The key features are heavy vaginal bleeding, cramping lower abdominal pain, an open cervical os, and visible products of conception. However, the ultrasound findings of an intrauterine gestational sac with fetal cardiac activity, albeit bradycardic, present a crucial detail. The most likely diagnosis among the options given is an \u003Cstrong\u003Einevitable miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einevitable miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by vaginal bleeding, an open cervix, and the presence of an intrauterine gestational sac with fetal cardiac activity on ultrasound. In this case, despite the presence of fetal cardiac activity (though bradycardic at 60 beats per minute), the open cervix and visible products of conception indicate that the miscarriage process has begun and is likely to progress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethreatened miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E presents with vaginal bleeding, but the cervical os remains closed and normal fetal cardiac activity is present on ultrasound. While this patient does have fetal cardiac activity, her open cervix and the bradycardic fetal heart rate rule out a threatened miscarriage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eincomplete miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by partial expulsion of the products of conception, with some tissue remaining in the uterus. However, in an incomplete miscarriage, there would typically be no fetal cardiac activity present on ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E is diagnosed when there is no intrauterine gestational sac visible on ultrasound. In this case, an intrauterine gestational sac with fetal cardiac activity is clearly visible, ruling out an ectopic pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emissed miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as a silent miscarriage, occurs when the fetus has died but has not been expelled. It is typically asymptomatic and diagnosed incidentally on ultrasound. The cervix remains closed, and there is no fetal cardiac activity. This patient\u0027s symptoms of bleeding and pain, along with the open cervix and presence of fetal cardiac activity (even though bradycardic), are not consistent with a missed miscarriage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of an open cervix, visible products of conception, ongoing bleeding, and ultrasound findings of an intrauterine pregnancy with bradycardic fetal heart rate are most consistent with an inevitable miscarriage. Despite the presence of fetal cardiac activity, the open cervix, bleeding, and significantly slow fetal heart rate indicate that the miscarriage process has begun and is likely to continue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["An inevitable miscarriage occurs when there is an open cervix and bleeding, with an intrauterine gestational sac seen on ultrasound and fetal cardiac activity present, even if bradycardic.","A threatened miscarriage is characterised by vaginal bleeding, a closed cervix, and the presence of normal fetal cardiac activity on ultrasound."],"references":["Sapra KJ, Joseph KS, Galea S, et al. Signs and Symptoms of Early Pregnancy Loss. Reprod Sci 2017; 24:502.","ACOG Practice Bulletin No. 200 Summary: Early Pregnancy Loss. Obstet Gynecol 2018; 132:1311.","Ectopic pregnancy and miscarriage: diagnosis and initial management. In: NICE guideline [NG126] [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng126","Bleeding \u0026 Pain in Early Pregnancy. Ectopic Pregnancy, Miscarriage \u0026 PUL. In: South Australian Perinatal Practice Guideline [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/fead0f004ee4554cb7ecbfd150ce4f37/Bleeding+in+Early...;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-fead0f004ee4554cb7ecbfd150ce4f37-p4bu9Q"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2511"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-19T14:33:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-19T14:36:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2511"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53314"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position